# Test authoring rules

## File and test naming
- Test files: `test_*.py`. Test functions: `test_<scenario>_<expected>` (e.g. `test_full_purchase_flow_under_budget`).
- One file per high-level scenario family. Don't dump everything into one mega-file.

## Markers (declared in `pytest.ini`)
- `@pytest.mark.e2e` for full purchase flow tests.
- `@pytest.mark.smoke` for fast sanity tests.
- `@pytest.mark.search`, `@pytest.mark.cart` for area-specific tests.
- `@pytest.mark.data_driven` when the test reads from `data/*.yaml`.

## Allure
- Wrap each high-level phase in `with allure.step("..."):`.
- Add `@allure.epic`, `@allure.feature`, `@allure.story` once per test class/function.
- For parameterized tests use `allure.dynamic.parameter(...)` to expose the inputs in the report.

## What tests MUST do
- Use the `page` fixture (or `guest_page` to bypass login).
- Call into `src/flows/` for the four required user-flow functions; do NOT instantiate page objects directly in a test unless you're testing the page itself.
- Fail with a descriptive message: `assert x == y, f"got {x!r}, expected {y!r}"`.

## What tests MUST NOT do
- Use `page.locator(...)` or any direct Playwright API. That belongs in pages/components.
- Hard-code credentials. Read them from `.env` via `Settings`.
- Use `time.sleep`.
- Read or modify files outside the project root.

## Data-driven tests
- Load YAML in a module-level helper (see `tests/test_search_data_driven.py` for the pattern).
- Pass a single `scenario` dict per parametrize id; never pass tuples - dicts read better in failure output.
